# WPF PostgreSQL AppStatus / Sql pattern (required)

Any new feature that needs to read from or write to the client's PostgreSQL database MUST follow this pattern end-to-end (frontend, query catalogue, and optional schema migration) so the codebase stays consistent with the existing Staff and Access implementation.

## Core rule

All data access goes through `App.aps` only:

```csharp
var cn = App.aps.LocalConnectionstring(App.aps.propertyBranchCode);

var dt = App.aps.pda.GetDataTable(
    cn,
    App.aps.sql.SelectAllUsers(includeInactive: false),
    commandTimeoutSeconds: 60);

var encrypted = App.aps.crypt.DoEncrypt(newPlainPassword);
App.aps.Execute(cn, App.aps.sql.UpdateUserPassword(userId, encrypted, App.aps.signedOnUserId));
```

`App.aps` is the single `AppStatus` instance constructed in `App.OnStartup`. It owns:

- `App.aps.pda` — the `PosDataAccess` ODBC executor (already provided by the client). It is **stateless with respect to the connection string**: every CRUD call takes the compact string explicitly.
- `App.aps.sql` — the `Sql` query catalogue (every SQL string in the solution lives as a method here).
- `App.aps.crypt` — the `Crypt` instance used to encrypt/decrypt `users.password`. There is no `PasswordHasher`; by client decree all password save/display/seed/reseed paths use `crypt.DoEncrypt` / `crypt.DoDecrypt`.
- `App.aps.signedOnUserId` — the integer `users.user_id` that is stamped into `auth_user_id` on writes.
- `App.aps.LocalConnectionstring(App.aps.propertyBranchCode)` — the **only** source for the branch-qualified compact connection string. Call it once at the top of the method and thread the result through every `pda.*`, `Execute`, `ExecuteStrict`, and `Query` call in that scope. There is no hidden default anywhere in `PosDataAccess` or `AppStatus`. **External callers (anywhere outside `AppStatus.cs`) MUST always pass `App.aps.propertyBranchCode` explicitly** — the client's wider codebase has other `LocalConnectionstring` overloads, and the parameterless form here creates cross-assembly ambiguity.

## Forbidden

- Do NOT instantiate `PosDataAccess` yourself in UserControls, view-models, or `OpsServices*Store` classes.
- Do NOT build SQL strings inline anywhere outside `Sql.cs`. No `"SELECT ... FROM ..."` literals in `.xaml.cs` files, domain services, or stores. If the query does not exist yet, add a method to `Sql.cs` first and call it.
- Do NOT introduce new `Guid` keys for users/staff. User identity is the integer `public.users.user_id`. Operations types key staff by `int` (`OpsEmployee.Id`, `OpsScheduledShift.EmployeeId`, `OpsFloorTable.AssignedWaiterId`, `OpsFloorTable.OpsServerId`).
- Do NOT write plain-text passwords to `users.password`. Encrypt them with `App.aps.crypt.DoEncrypt(plain)` before persisting, and decrypt for display with `App.aps.crypt.DoDecrypt(stored)`. `PasswordHasher` has been removed — do not reintroduce it or any other hashing scheme for the user password column.
- Do NOT call `PosDataAccess` or `AppStatus.Execute` / `ExecuteStrict` / `Query` without passing the compact connection string obtained from `App.aps.LocalConnectionstring(App.aps.propertyBranchCode)`. There are no parameterless overloads on the data-access methods; the first argument of every data-access method is the compact string by contract.
- Do NOT call `App.aps.LocalConnectionstring()` without an argument from outside `AppStatus.cs`. Always pass `App.aps.propertyBranchCode` so the call is unambiguous against other `LocalConnectionstring` overloads in the client's wider codebase. Only code inside `AppStatus` itself is allowed to use the parameterless form.
- Do NOT run DDL (`ALTER TABLE`, `CREATE TABLE`, …) from the app at startup or anywhere else. The app only runs DML.

## Required conventions

- Writes that are part of a single logical operation MUST use `PosDataAccess.SetSql(..., transactional: true)`. The `AppStatus.Execute(sql)` helper already sets this by default — prefer it over calling `pda.SetSql` directly.
- Writes stamp `auth_user_id = App.aps.signedOnUserId` and `affected_ts = now()`. `Sql` methods already do this; do not bypass them by writing your own UPDATE statements.
- Reads go through the cached stores where they exist (`StaffAccessStore`, `OpsServicesStore`). New stores should follow the same shape: lazy load via `App.aps.pda`, raise `DataChanged` after mutations, expose `ReloadFromDb()`.
- Demo / fixture rows are inserted with `is_seed = TRUE` and deleted by `AppStatus.ReseedDummyDataIfEnabled()` when `SeedDummyDataOnStartup = true` in `App.config`. Live rows (`is_seed = FALSE`) are never touched by reseed. New seed data must use the same toggle.
- Passwords and any other sensitive text MUST be encrypted (`App.aps.crypt.DoEncrypt`) or redacted before being passed to `Sql` methods. Never log them in plain text.
- Any literal that comes from user input has to be composed through `Sql.Quote`, `Sql.Int`, `Sql.Bool`, `Sql.Ts`, `Sql.Nullable` — never by string concatenation with `$"..."` interpolation.
- **Soft delete is the default.** User and role deletions MUST go through `Sql.SoftDeleteUser` / `Sql.SoftDeleteRole`, which set `deleted = TRUE`, `deleted_ts = now()`, `deleted_user_id = App.aps.signedOnUserId`, `active = FALSE`. Reads filter `COALESCE(deleted, FALSE) = FALSE`. `user_id` values of soft-deleted users are NEVER reused — Operations history stays referentially valid. Hard `DELETE FROM public.users/roles` is reserved for `is_seed = TRUE` dev data only (see `DeleteAllSeedRows`).
- Boolean column reads MUST accept the PostgreSQL ODBC driver's string form (`"0"`, `"1"`, `"t"`, `"f"`, `"true"`, `"false"`) as well as real `System.Boolean`. Use the `StaffAccessStore.AsBool` helper pattern — do NOT call `Convert.ToBoolean(obj)` directly on driver output.
- **Audit writes identify the terminal by its real IPv4.** Use `App.aps.LocalIpAddress` (not a hard-coded sample, not `Dns.GetHostName`, not the MAC address) as `ipAddress:` on every `Sql.InsertAuditTrail` call. The helper returns the primary operational Ethernet/Wi-Fi adapter's IPv4 and is cached for 60 s. When no usable NIC is found it returns an empty string — pass `null` in that case so the column is `NULL`, not `""`. The `ip_address` column in `public.audit_trail` **is** the terminal identifier; do not introduce a separate `device_id` or similar column.

## PostgreSQL 9.3 compatibility (hard requirement)

The client's production database is **PostgreSQL 9.3**. Every SQL statement emitted by this app — migration scripts under `WpfUserControlFramework/Migrations/*.sql` AND runtime strings built in `Sql.cs` — MUST run as-is on 9.3. When in doubt, favour the older pattern; never assume 9.4+ features.

**Forbidden syntax (PG 9.3 does NOT have it):**

| Feature | Introduced in | Use instead |
|---|---|---|
| `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (col) DO NOTHING / DO UPDATE` | 9.5 | `INSERT INTO t (...) SELECT <vals> WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM t WHERE <key> = <val>)` |
| `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS` | 9.6 | `DO $$ BEGIN IF NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM information_schema.columns WHERE table_schema='public' AND table_name='<t>' AND column_name='<c>') THEN ALTER TABLE public.<t> ADD COLUMN <c> <type>; END IF; END$$;` |
| `CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS` | 9.5 | `DO $$ BEGIN IF NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM pg_indexes WHERE schemaname='public' AND indexname='<ix>') THEN CREATE INDEX <ix> ON ...; END IF; END$$;` |
| `FILTER (WHERE ...)` on aggregates | 9.4 | `SUM(CASE WHEN <cond> THEN <expr> ELSE 0 END)` equivalents |
| `GROUPING SETS` / `CUBE` / `ROLLUP` | 9.5 | Multiple `UNION ALL` subqueries |
| `TABLESAMPLE` | 9.5 | `ORDER BY random() LIMIT n` or modulo-based sampling |
| `jsonb` type, `jsonb_*` operators (`->`, `->>` exist on `json` since 9.3) | 9.4 | Plain `json` type only |
| `gen_random_uuid()` (from pgcrypto) | 9.4 | `uuid_generate_v4()` from `uuid-ossp`, or have the app generate the UUID |
| Correlated `UPDATE ... FROM` / writable CTE shortcuts newer than 9.3 | 9.4+ | Stick to 9.3-documented UPDATE/DELETE syntax |

**Allowed and used heavily** (all available in 9.3 or earlier):

- `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS`, `CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS`, `DROP ... IF EXISTS`
- `DO $$ ... $$` PL/pgSQL blocks (since 9.0)
- `WITH` / `WITH RECURSIVE` CTEs (8.4+)
- Partial indexes (`CREATE INDEX ... WHERE ...`)
- `RETURNING` in DML (8.2+)
- `LATERAL` joins (9.3)
- `json` type with `->`, `->>` operators (9.3)
- `AT TIME ZONE`, `COALESCE`, `LIMIT`, `OFFSET`, window functions

**Patterns the reference implementation uses — copy these verbatim for new features:**

```sql
-- Idempotent row insert, 9.3-safe (replaces ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING):
INSERT INTO public.roles (role_id, descr, auth_user_id, active, deleted, affected_ts, is_seed)
SELECT 1, 'Admin', 1, TRUE, FALSE, now(), FALSE
WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.roles WHERE role_id = 1);

-- Idempotent column add, 9.3-safe (replaces ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS):
DO $$
BEGIN
    IF NOT EXISTS (
        SELECT 1 FROM information_schema.columns
        WHERE table_schema = 'public' AND table_name = 'users' AND column_name = 'job_title'
    ) THEN
        ALTER TABLE public.users ADD COLUMN job_title text;
    END IF;
END$$;

-- Idempotent index create, 9.3-safe (replaces CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS):
DO $$
BEGIN
    IF NOT EXISTS (
        SELECT 1 FROM pg_indexes
        WHERE schemaname = 'public' AND indexname = 'ix_users_not_deleted'
    ) THEN
        CREATE INDEX ix_users_not_deleted ON public.users (user_id) WHERE deleted = FALSE;
    END IF;
END$$;
```

`Sql.cs` builds the same `INSERT ... WHERE NOT EXISTS` pattern at runtime for `EnsureFixedRoles`, `EnsureBootstrapSystemUser`, `InsertSeedUsers`, and `EnsurePhaseIdUpsert`. Do not reintroduce `ON CONFLICT` in either place.

## Schema changes

If a feature needs new columns or tables:

1. Create `WpfUserControlFramework/Migrations/<yyyy-mm-dd>_<feature>.sql` using the 9.3-safe patterns above. Start the file with a `ROLLBACK; BEGIN;` pair and end with `COMMIT;` so the client DBA can paste the whole script into psql in one go.
2. `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS` is allowed; `ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS` and `CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS` are NOT — use DO-block guards instead.
3. Seed rows via `INSERT ... SELECT ... WHERE NOT EXISTS`, never `ON CONFLICT`.
4. Update `Sql.cs` to read/write the new columns. Any runtime upserts there must also use the `WHERE NOT EXISTS` pattern.
5. Do NOT run the migration from the app. The app assumes the schema is already present (it tolerates missing columns via `COALESCE(...)` in `Sql.SelectAllUsers`-style read queries when safe).

## End-to-end expectation for new features

Every new feature ships, in the same change:

1. The UI (UserControls, XAML) that consumes the data.
2. New methods on `Sql` with all SQL for the feature.
3. A dated `.sql` migration file if the schema has to change.
4. No raw ODBC, no raw SQL outside `Sql`, no new `Guid` keys for users.

The Staff and Access implementation (`WpfUserControlFramework/Controls/Staff and Access`) plus `WpfUserControlFramework/Utils/AppStatus.cs`, `Sql.cs`, `PosDataAccess.cs`, and `Crypt.cs` are the reference implementation for this rule.
